		<div class="right"><a href="index.html"><img src="../sle.png" alt="SLE 2025"></a><br><code>sle2025/paper13</code></div>
			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2025</a> paper:</span><br><i>Optimize Effect Handling for Tail-resumption with Stack Unwinding</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/YuzeFu.html">Yuze Fu</a>, <a href="../profile/ShigeruChiba.html">Shigeru Chiba</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1145/3732771.3742721">10.1145/3732771.3742721</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4d.html"><span class="tagM">T4D: Interpretation</span></a><ul><li> Effect handlers are a runtime control-flow mechanism, and the paper proposes a concrete runtime implementation strategy.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5f.html"><span class="tagL">T5F: Performance</span></a><ul><li> The goal is to reduce overhead for tail-resumptive handlers, with performance as the main evaluation dimension.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t1c.html"><span class="tagL">T1C: Behavioural Semantics</span></a><ul><li> The work is about executable semantics of algebraic effects/handlers and how they are realized operationally.
</li></ul></li></ul>
